    .area-grid div p { font-size: 14px; color: var(--muted); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
    .area-grid div a { color: var(--red); text-decoration: underline; }
    .faq { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 18px 0; }
    .faq:first-of-type { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
    .faq summary { font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; list-style: none; padding-right: 24px; position: relative; }
    .faq summary::after { content: "+"; position: absolute; right: 0; top: 0; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 400; color: var(--red); }
    .faq[open] summary::after { content: "−"; }
    .faq p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.75; margin: 12px 0 0; }
    .faq p :global(a) { color: var(--red); text-decoration: underline; }
    .related-links { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 20px 0 0; }
    .related-links li { padding: 10px 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 15px; }
    .related-links li:first-child { border-top: none; }
    .related-links a { color: var(--text); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
    .related-links a:hover { color: var(--red); }
    .bottom-cta { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 60px 0; text-align: center; }
    .bottom-cta h2 { color: #fff; margin-bottom: 14px; }
    .bottom-cta p { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.65); max-width: 540px; margin: 0 auto 26px; }
    .bottom-cta .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 12px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  </style>

  <div class="call-banner">
    <span>AHT chest freezer or merchandiser down? Call now for same-day service:</span>
    <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="phone-lg">{MAIN_PHONE}</a>
  </div>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero"><div class="wrap">
          <div class="crumb"><a href="/">Home</a> › <a href="/brands/">Brands</a> › AHT Cooling Systems</div>
          <h1>AHT Cooling Systems Repair</h1>
          <p class="lede">
            AHT Cooling Systems is the Austrian plug-in refrigeration specialist our techs service across LA grocery,
            convenience, and specialty retail — MALTA mode-switchable chest freezers at Trader Joe's and Aldi, MIAMI
            panoramic-glass island merchandisers at convenience-store chains, RIO ice-cream freezers at specialty
            grocers, ATHEN upright merchandisers at Whole Foods and Bristol Farms. Daikin Group parent since 2017,
            Rottenmann Austria headquarters, US office in Ladson South Carolina. Same-day LA dispatch, $120 commercial
            diagnostic waived with the repair.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-cta">
            <a href={`tel:${MAIN_PHONE_TEL}`} class="btn btn-primary">Call {MAIN_PHONE}</a>
            <a href="/contact/" class="btn btn-ghost">Request a Visit</a>
          </div>
          <ul class="hero-facts">
            <li><b>AHT specialty service</b> — MALTA, MIAMI, RIO, ATHEN, AC-S lines</li>
            <li><b>$120 commercial diagnostic</b> — waived when you authorize the repair</li>
            <li><b>LA grocery / retail cluster</b> — Trader Joe's, Whole Foods, Aldi, Lidl, Bristol Farms, Erewhon</li>
            <li><b>Plug-in self-contained</b> — no remote compressor, no glycol, no rooftop condensing</li>
          </ul>
        </div></section>

  <BrandBranchesGrid />

  <section class="trust-bar">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>CSLB #1138898 · Insured</span>
      <span>Same-day in 5 SoCal counties</span>
      <span>Commercial diagnostic $120 · waived with repair</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #1 — POSITIONING -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>AHT Cooling Systems — the plug-in commercial refrigeration specialist</h2>
      <p>
        Most commercial refrigeration in LA runs on remote-compressor architecture — the compressor sits on the roof
        or in a mechanical closet, refrigerant lines run to the cooler, the service call touches three or four
        locations across the building. AHT takes the opposite approach: self-contained plug-in refrigeration where
        the entire system (compressor, condenser, evaporator, controls) lives inside the cabinet. Plug it into a
        120V outlet, and the unit refrigerates. No piping, no glycol, no rooftop work.
      </p>
      <p>
        That design choice is why AHT dominates a specific slice of the LA retail refrigeration landscape — grocery
        and convenience stores that want seasonal merchandising flexibility without a permanent refrigeration
        install. The unit drops in, it drops out, it can be relocated across a store remodel without pulling
        refrigerant lines. LA grocery buyers at Trader Joe's, Aldi, Lidl, Whole Foods, Bristol Farms, and Erewhon
        specify AHT for that reason. The trade-off: when the self-contained unit fails, the entire system comes
        out for service access. That's the repair profile our techs run AHT against.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're one of the few LA appliance-repair providers that actually runs AHT service dispatch. The brand is a
        niche — Austrian, Daikin-owned, mostly European market focus — and the LA service-provider SERP is thin.
        Most of the national companies that appear on AHT searches are either the OEM directly or national service
        networks without LA field presence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #2 — WHAT WE FIX -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>What our techs fix on AHT plug-in units</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Self-contained plug-in refrigeration has a different failure profile than walk-in or reach-in systems.
        Here's where AHT units fail and how our techs diagnose each.
      </p>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Compressor thermal overload trip</h3>
        <p>
          The #1 AHT call. The self-contained compressor lives inside the cabinet with minimal airflow clearance, and
          when the condenser coil clogs with retail-environment dust, the compressor runs against rising head
          pressure until the thermal overload safety trips. Unit goes warm, retail staff reports "it stopped working."
          Our diagnostic pulls the cabinet, inspects the condenser, cleans the coil, tests the compressor with a
          clamp meter, and verifies the thermal safety is functional. Quarterly condenser cleaning on high-use units
          prevents this call almost entirely.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Door and lid gasket failure</h3>
        <p>
          MALTA chest lids and MIAMI sliding-glass panels get heavy door-cycle wear in grocery environments. Gasket
          compression loss lets warm retail-floor air infiltrate, the compressor runs longer to compensate, and the
          product surface warms visibly to the customer. We carry common AHT gasket profiles on the truck; less-common
          gaskets order from Daikin's US network.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>LED lighting and control boards</h3>
        <p>
          Merchandising-critical failure mode. When the interior LEDs on a MIAMI or RIO go dark mid-shift, product
          visibility tanks and sales drop immediately. The LED driver sits inside the cabinet structure and usually
          requires partial unit disassembly to access. Control board failures follow a similar repair profile —
          we replace the board, re-commission the temperature setpoints, and verify the diagnostic readout matches
          spec.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>Evaporator and defrost-cycle issues</h3>
        <p>
          Frost buildup on the evaporator that doesn't clear on the defrost cycle, water pooling at the cabinet base
          from a blocked drain, uneven cooling across the cabinet interior. Common on older MALTA and RIO units
          where the defrost heater has aged past its service life. Fix: heater replacement, drain clear, sometimes
          controller recalibration.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #3 — PRODUCT LINES -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>AHT product lines — MALTA, MIAMI, RIO, ATHEN</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Four core product families cover most of AHT's LA retail footprint. Each has a specific retail use case and
        a specific service profile.
      </p>
      <div class="model-grid">
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>MALTA — mode-switchable chest</h3>
          <p>185-cm chest unit with freeze / chill / meat mode switching. Seasonal merchandising flexibility (ice
          cream in summer, meat display in winter). Common at grocery operators who rotate frozen merchandising
          categories.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>MIAMI — panoramic island merchandiser</h3>
          <p>Large sliding-glass island with panoramic merchandising view. The convenience-store / gas-station
          beverage and grab-and-go staple. Heaviest door-cycle count in the AHT catalog.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>RIO — ice cream & sliding glass freezer</h3>
          <p>Dedicated ice-cream and frozen-novelty line. Variants include RIO S100, RIO S125, RIO H 68S sized to
          different retail footprints. Coldest operating temperature in the AHT range.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>ATHEN — upright merchandiser</h3>
          <p>Glass-door upright format for vertical retail presentation. Premium beverage, prepared-food, or
          specialty-frozen merchandising. Closer service profile to a True GDM or Beverage-Air DR than to the
          horizontal chest freezers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>AC-S and legacy lines</h3>
          <p>Older-generation AHT commercial refrigeration equipment still in the LA field. Parts for AC-S and
          legacy units route from Daikin's US network with longer lead times than current production.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <h3>KIGALI XL (current production)</h3>
          <p>AHT's newer award-winning model line, part of the post-Daikin-acquisition product refresh. Growing
          share of new retail installations at premium LA grocery operators.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #4 — DAIKIN -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>The Daikin acquisition (2017) — parts supply and service outlook</h2>
      <p>
        Daikin Industries, the Japanese multinational that built its US HVAC presence through the Goodman Global
        acquisition in 2012, acquired AHT Cooling Systems in 2017 as part of Daikin's expansion into commercial
        refrigeration outside of Japan and Europe. AHT retained its Rottenmann Austria engineering headquarters
        and product identity, but parts supply and service operations restructured under Daikin's global network.
        For LA operators, the practical effect is a US-based parts channel through Daikin's distribution partners
        (routed through the AHT Ladson SC corporate office) plus direct-from-Rottenmann supply for specialty
        components.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Daikin acquisition also unlocked broader refrigeration-technology integration — AHT has access to
        Daikin's inverter compressor research and HFC-transition refrigerant work, which shows up in current-production
        AHT units running lower-GWP refrigerants. For a service provider in LA, that matters because it affects
        which EPA certifications are relevant on which repair — the current-production AHT catalog increasingly
        runs refrigerants that require different handling from the pre-2017 HFC-standard units still in the field.
        Our techs track the refrigerant split model-by-model.
      </p>
      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>AHT is NOT part of Ali Group</h3>
        <p>
          Clarifying this because SERP content on commercial refrigeration frequently conflates parent companies.
          AHT is Daikin-owned. The Ali Group commercial refrigeration family (Beverage-Air, Delfield, Manitowoc,
          Kolpak, Master-Bilt, Nor-Lake post-2022) runs a different parts supply chain, a different service network,
          and different warranty program. True Refrigeration is its own independent. Hoshizaki is Japanese but
          separate from AHT. Five distinct corporate trees in one LA service-provider's dispatch day.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- H2 #5 — LA GROCERY CLUSTER -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>LA grocery and retail cluster — where AHT lives in LA</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Our AHT dispatch map across LA grocery and specialty retail. Six operator segments drive the bulk of AHT
        service calls.
      </p>
      <div class="area-grid">
        <div>
          <h4>Trader Joe's locations</h4>
          <p>AHT plug-in units show up in seasonal ice-cream and frozen-merchandising rotations across LA Trader
          Joe's stores. Our dispatch covers Westside, Valley, and Westside-adjacent locations.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Aldi and Lidl</h4>
          <p>European grocery chains that brought AHT from their European supply chain into US expansion. Frozen
          grocery aisles and seasonal merchandising both run on AHT plug-in.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Whole Foods and Bristol Farms</h4>
          <p>Premium grocery formats running ATHEN uprights and MALTA chest units in prepared-frozen and
          premium-frozen sections. Austrian engineering + Daikin ownership lands well at these operators.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Erewhon (premium specialty grocery)</h4>
          <p>LA's high-end specialty grocer uses AHT for curated frozen merchandising where visual presentation
          and temperature precision both matter.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Convenience stores and gas stations</h4>
